Deep Learning Ensembles for VIX Forecasting: A Multi-Horizon N-BEATS Approach

We forecast the VIX index using a multi-horizon N-BEATS deep-learning pipeline in a 9-model ensemble stack using PyTorch. Each model predicts the VIX Close value of the next day and we then aggregate different model forecasts in a median to power-up our ensemble stack.

We use Dropout layers for regularization, ADAM with L2 regularization as our optimizer, Huber Loss as our loss function and early-stopping to reduce training time. We train our model on an NVIDIA GeForce RTX 4080 GPU by utilizing the CUDA framework.

Finally, we test our model against the actual future values and calculate the Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) to measure the performance of our forecasts. The result is a simple, fast, and accurate deep-learning forecaster for market volatility.

The VIX, or CBOE Volatility Index, is a widely followed indicator of the market's expectation of future volatility as implied by S&P 500 index options. The VIX is designed to quantify expected stock market volatility in the near term, serving as a forward-looking gauge based on options market activity. Its quoted value reflects the markets consensus for the annualized percentage change in the S&P 500 over the next 30 days, derived from options-pricing models and real-time options data. In essence, it is a volatility index calculated from S&P 500 options, with each options price embodying the markets expectation of 30-day future volatility.

Because volatility is generally non-stationary, regime-dependent and a single model can cover only one timescale; we train several N-BEATS instances with different lookback lengths $n \times H, \quad n=2, 3, \cdots, 9 \quad$ to capture short-term jitters and longer-term structure, then combine them with a robust median ensemble.

We are going to use the N-BEATS architecture by Boris N. Oreshkin, Dmitri Carpov, Nicolas Chapados, Yoshua Bengio, which has proven immense success in prediction problems in univariate time series domain. N-BEATS is a powerful deep learning architecture for time series forecasting because it leverages a simple-to-understand but highly expressive fully connected network without reliance on time-series-specific feature engineering. Its block-based structure, where each block provides both a backcast and a forecast, allows iterative residual learning that improves the prediction increasingly in each iteration. The doubly residual stacking of the novel architecture can propagate gradients successfully and allows the model to decompose the input signal into significant components, such as trend and seasonality, without sacrificing performance. All this is achieved with flexibility, interpretability, and state-of-the-art accuracy on a broad variety of forecasting benchmarks, which makes N-BEATS a compelling choice for time series analysis.

(Reference: https://arxiv.org/abs/1905.10437 - N-BEATS: Neural basis expansion analysis for interpretable time series forecasting, Boris N. Oreshkin, Dmitri Carpov, Nicolas Chapados, Yoshua Bengio)

(Reference: https://arxiv.org/abs/1905.10437 - N-BEATS: Neural basis expansion analysis for interpretable time series forecasting, Boris N. Oreshkin, Dmitri Carpov, Nicolas Chapados, Yoshua Bengio)

We begin by designing the Block component of the N-BEATS architecture, the core unit responsible for transforming historical input data into both backcast (reconstructed past) and forecast (predicted future) outputs.

For simplicity, the intermediate layer sizes are chosen as multiples of $256$, a common convention in deep learning, while hyperparameter tuning is left out of scope for this demonstration.

To enhance the models ability to generalize and avoid overfitting, we introduce Dropout regularization after key fully connected layers. The blocks output is then split into two parallel linear transformations: one producing the backcast signal and the other generating the forecast for the defined horizon $H$.

In[126]:
class NBEATSBlock(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, H, n, dropout_prob=0.1):
        """
        Parameters:
        H (int): Forecast horizon (number of future time steps to predict)
        n (int): How many times the forecast horizon to look back
        """
        super().__init__()
        self.stem = nn.Sequential(  # input size: (batch_size, 1, H*n)
            nn.Linear(in_features=H*n, out_features=512), nn.ReLU(), nn.Dropout(dropout_prob),
            nn.Linear(in_features=512, out_features=1024), nn.ReLU(), nn.Dropout(dropout_prob),
            nn.Linear(in_features=1024, out_features=512), nn.ReLU(), nn.Dropout(dropout_prob),
            nn.Linear(in_features=512, out_features=256), nn.ReLU()
        )

        # In generic architecture, the backcast and forecast transformations are just linear layers
        self.backcast = nn.Linear(in_features=256, out_features=H*n)
        self.forecast = nn.Linear(in_features=256, out_features=H)

    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.stem(x)
        x_bc = self.backcast(x)
        x_fc = self.forecast(x)

        return x_bc, x_fc

Next, we construct the Stack component of the N-BEATS architecture, which is essentially a sequence of Blocks.

While PyTorchs nn.Sequential is a convenient tool for chaining modules together in a purely feed-forward mannerwhere the output of one layer becomes the input to the nextit cannot handle our case directly. The reason is that each NBEATSBlock produces two outputs:

Backcast: the part of the input signal the block tries to reconstruct.

Forecast: the models prediction for the future horizon.

In our stack, the backcast must be subtracted from the current residual before passing it to the next block. This iterative residual update is at the heart of N-BEATS, but it requires custom control flow. Since nn.Sequential does not allow for such multi-output, state-updating logic, we instead use nn.ModuleList, which gives us full flexibility in the forward pass.

In the NBEATSStack implementation below, we:

  1. Initialize $K=30$ blocks in a ModuleList.

  2. Keep track of a running sum of forecasts across all blocks.

  3. Iteratively update the residual by removing the blocks backcast.

  4. Return the final residual and the aggregated forecast.

In[128]:
class NBEATSStack(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, K, H, n):
        """
        Parameters:
        K (int): Number of blocks in the stack
        H (int): Forecast horizon (number of future time steps to predict)
        n (int): How many times the forecast horizon to look back
        """
        super().__init__()
        self.blocks = nn.ModuleList([NBEATSBlock(H, n) for _ in range(K)])

    def forward(self, x):
        x_fc_sum = torch.zeros(x.size(0), H, dtype=x.dtype).to(x.device)
        residual = x  # start with the original input
        for block in self.blocks:
            x_bc, x_fc = block(residual)
            residual = residual - x_bc  # update residual using the blocks input
            x_fc_sum += x_fc
        return residual, x_fc_sum

Finally, we assemble the full N-BEATS architecture by stacking multiple NBEATSStack modules on top of each other. This hierarchical design is what allows the network to progressively refine its predictions. Each stack operates on the residual signal left by the previous stack, just as each block operates on the residual from the previous block. Moreover, forecasts from all stacks are aggregated to produce the final prediction.

The top-level NBEATS class therefore orchestrates the flow of information across the entire model:

  1. Initialization: We create $M=3$ stacks, each consisting of $K=30$ residual blocks.

  2. Forward Pass: The input passes through each stack sequentially. After each stack, we update the residual by removing the backcast, then add the stacks forecast to a running total.

  3. Output: The aggregated forecast from all stacks is returned as the models prediction.

In[130]:
class NBEATS(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, M, K, H, n):
        """
        Parameters:
        M (int): Number of stacks in the network
        K (int): Number of blocks in the stack
        H (int): Forecast horizon (number of future time steps to predict)
        n (int): How many times the forecast horizon to look back
        """
        super().__init__()
        self.H = H
        self.stacks = nn.ModuleList([NBEATSStack(K, H, n) for _ in range(M)])
    
    def forward(self, x):
        # Initialize forecast accumulator
        forecast_total = torch.zeros(x.size(0), self.H, 
                                  device=x.device, dtype=x.dtype)
        residual = x
        
        for stack in self.stacks:
            # Process through stack
            residual, stack_forecast = stack(residual)
            # Aggregate forecasts
            forecast_total += stack_forecast
            
        return forecast_total

With the N-BEATS architecture fully defined, using $M=3$ stacks and $K=30$ blocks in each stack, we now move to the training stage. The network contains more than 100 million trainable parameters, which makes it highly data-hungry. To ensure the model is exposed to a wide variety of market regimes, we train it on a long historical record of VIX closing values. This period spans from 2004 to 2024 and includes calm markets, sharp volatility spikes, and prolonged high-volatility episodes, allowing the model to learn from a broad spectrum of conditions.

For the evaluation phase, the final year of data is kept completely out of the training process and serves as a pure out-of-sample test set. This approach provides an unbiased assessment of the models forecasting ability in real-world conditions. The data is retrieved directly through the yfinance API, giving us clean and consistent time series for both the training and testing periods.

Because we have built up the final NBEATS class, we can move on to create our ensemble pack. We are going to build $9$ models with different lookback periods $n=2, 3, \cdots, 10$. Each configuration results in a unique input length, calculated as $H \times n$ where $H$ is the forecast horizon (in our case $H=1$). These models are then stored for later use, ensuring that we can efficiently train, evaluate, and deploy them without repeatedly reconstructing the architecture.

Then, we featurize our dataset with labels: for every day, previous $H \times n$ trading days will be used as features, and the next $H$ days will be used as labels. Note that in this study, we have set $H=1$, so our model is going to forecast only the next day.


















In[]:






def featurize_series_NBEATS(series, H, n):
    """
    Parameters:
    series (pd.Series): Time series to convert to PyTorch tensor
    H (int): Forecast horizon (number of future time steps to predict)
    n (int): How many times the forecast horizon to look back
    """
    series = series.values.astype(np.float32)

    # Create the feature tensor X by rolling the series n times
    num_rows = len(series) - H*n - H + 1
    X = np.zeros((num_rows, H*n))
    Y = np.zeros((num_rows, H))
    for i in range(num_rows):
        X[i, :] = series[i : i + H*n]
        Y[i, :] = series[i + H*n : i + H*n + H]

    X = torch.tensor(X, dtype=torch.float32)
    Y = torch.tensor(Y, dtype=torch.float32)

    return X, Y

























To make our model more robust and capable of generalizing to unseen data, we split the featurized dataset into training and validation sets. The training set is used to fit the model, while the validation set provides an unbiased check on its performance during each epoch.


We use a validation ratio of $0.2$, meaning $20 \% $ of the most recent data is set aside for validation, and the remaining $80 \%$ is used for training. This approach lets us track both training and validation losses side by side, helping us choose the best-performing model weights and reduce the risk of overfitting. Since we keep the data in chronological order, we also preserve the natural flow of time, which is essential in forecasting tasks.


















In[]:






def train_val_split(X, Y, val_size=0.2):
    """
    Parameters:
    X (torch.Tensor): Input feature tensor
    Y (torch.Tensor): Target tensor
    val_size (float): Proportion of the data to use for validation
    """
    num_train = int((1-val_size) * len(X))
    X_train, Y_train = X[:num_train], Y[:num_train]
    X_val, Y_val = X[num_train:], Y[num_train:]

    return X_train, Y_train, X_val, Y_val

























Then we initialize PyTorch TensorDataset and DataLoader objects to prepare our dataset for training, choosing a batch size of $1024$, also the chosen value in the paper.


















In[136]:






from torch.utils.data import TensorDataset, DataLoader

batch_size = 1024
loaders_dict = {}
for idx, (model_name, model) in enumerate(models_dict.items()):
    n = n_array[idx]
    X, Y = featurize_series_NBEATS(trainval_data, H, n)
    X_train, Y_train, X_val, Y_val = train_val_split(X, Y, val_size=0.2)
    loaders_dict[model_name] = {
        "train_loader":DataLoader(TensorDataset(X_train, Y_train), batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=True),
        "val_loader":DataLoader(TensorDataset(X_val, Y_val), batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=False)
    }

























We choose MAPE for our test performance metric but will not be using it as our main loss function. But you can always uncomment the MAPELoss() line in the training loop to try a different loss function for training.


















In[137]:






def calc_mape(y_true, y_pred, eps=1e-6):
    mape = torch.mean(torch.abs((y_true - y_pred) / (y_true + eps))) * 100
    return mape
    
class MAPELoss(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, eps=1e-8):
        super(MAPELoss, self).__init__()
        self.eps = eps  # to avoid division by zero

    def forward(self, y_pred, y_true):
        # y_pred: predicted values
        # y_true: actual values
        loss = torch.mean(torch.abs((y_true - y_pred) / (y_true + self.eps))) * 100
        return loss

























With the ensemble initialized, we proceed to the training phase, where each of the $9$ N-BEATS models is trained independently. Throughout training, we track both training and validation losses at every epoch to monitor learning progress and detect overfitting.


Given that each model contains more than 100 million trainable parameters, saving intermediate results is essential. We implement early stopping to prevent wasted computation and to improve generalization: if the validation loss does not improve for $20$ consecutive epochs (patience parameter), training halts and the best-performing weights are preserved.


In addition, a learning rate scheduler is employed to gradually reduce the learning rate when progress stalls, specifically halving it after three epochs without improvement in validation loss. This helps the optimizer converge more reliably to a well-performing solution.


The final outcome of this process is two saved versions for each model: the best checkpoint according to validation loss and the final state at the end of training, ensuring flexibility for later evaluation and ensemble integration.


















In[138]:






def train_NBEATS(train_loader, val_loader, model, device, model_name):
    num_epochs = 100
    train_losses = []
    val_losses = []
    best_val_loss = float('inf')
    patience = 20
    epochs_without_improve = 0

    loss_func = torch.nn.SmoothL1Loss(beta=0.5)  # Huber
    # loss_func = MAPELoss()
    optimizer = torch.optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=1e-3, weight_decay=1e-4)
    scheduler = torch.optim.lr_scheduler.ReduceLROnPlateau(optimizer, mode='min', factor=0.5, patience=3)

    save_path_best = f"best_nbeats_weights_{model_name}.pth"
    save_path_final = f"nbeats_model_weights_final_{model_name}.pth"

    for epoch in range(num_epochs):
        # Training loop
        model.train()
        running_train_loss = 0.0
        for inputs, targets in train_loader:
            inputs = inputs.to(device) # shape: (batch_size, H*n)
            targets = targets.to(device) # shape: (batch_size, H)
            
            optimizer.zero_grad()
            forecasts = model(inputs) # forecast shape: (batch_size, H)
            loss = loss_func(forecasts, targets)
            loss.backward()
            optimizer.step()
            running_train_loss += loss.item() * inputs.size(0)
        
        epoch_train_loss = running_train_loss / len(train_loader.dataset)
        train_losses.append(epoch_train_loss)
        
        # Validation loop
        model.eval()
        running_val_loss = 0.0
        with torch.no_grad():
            for inputs, targets in val_loader:
                inputs = inputs.to(device)
                targets = targets.to(device)
                forecasts = model(inputs)
                loss = loss_func(forecasts, targets)
                running_val_loss += loss.item() * inputs.size(0)
        epoch_val_loss = running_val_loss / len(val_loader.dataset)
        val_losses.append(epoch_val_loss)
        scheduler.step(epoch_val_loss)
        
        print(f"Epoch {epoch+1}/{num_epochs} - Train Loss: {epoch_train_loss:.4f} - Val Loss: {epoch_val_loss:.4f}")
        
        # Early stopping: check if validation loss improved
        if epoch_val_loss < best_val_loss:
            best_val_loss = epoch_val_loss
            epochs_without_improve = 0
            # Optionally save the best model here
            torch.save(model.state_dict(), save_path_best)
            print(f"    Best model weights so far saved to {save_path_best}")
        else:
            epochs_without_improve += 1
            if epochs_without_improve >= patience:
                print(f"Early stopping triggered after {epoch+1} epochs.")
                break

    # Save the final model weights
    torch.save(model.state_dict(), save_path_final)
    print(f"    Final model weights saved to {save_path_final}")

    return train_losses, val_losses

train_losses_dict = {}
val_losses_dict = {}
for model_name, model in models_dict.items():
    train_loader = loaders_dict[model_name]["train_loader"]
    val_loader = loaders_dict[model_name]["val_loader"]
    train_losses, val_losses = train_NBEATS(train_loader, val_loader, model, device, model_name)
    train_losses_dict[model_name] = train_losses
    val_losses_dict[model_name] = val_losses

With the models set to evaluation mode, we generated forecasts for the entire test period and compared them against the actual observed values. Performance was measured using the Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE), which provided a clear, scale-independent metric for accuracy. The results showed strong consistency across the ensemble: MAPE values clustered between roughly $6.3 \%$ and $7.2 \%$ for most models, with only one outlier above $10 \%$.


The forecasts from each model were then aligned with the actual time series in a single pd.DataFrame, which also included a rolling median forecast across all models. This median served as the ensembles aggregate prediction, reducing the influence of any single models potential over or underestimation on a given day. The final DataFrame structure allowed for direct comparison between actual market values, individual model predictions, and the ensembles median output.

def build_rolling_from_series(preds, test_series, L_back):
    fc = preds.detach().cpu().numpy() if torch.is_tensor(preds) else np.asarray(preds)
    N, H = fc.shape
    idx = test_series.index
    verif_index = pd.DatetimeIndex(idx[L_back : L_back + (N + H - 1)])

    T = len(verif_index)
    forecast_latest = np.full(T, np.nan); latest_origin = -np.ones(T, int)
    chosen_h = np.full(T, np.nan)
    actual = test_series.loc[verif_index].to_numpy(dtype=float)

    for i in range(N):
        for h in range(H):
            t = i + h
            if t >= T:
                break
            if i >= latest_origin[t]:
                forecast_latest[t] = fc[i, h]
                latest_origin[t] = i
                chosen_h[t] = h + 1

    df = pd.DataFrame({"Actual": actual, "Forecast_latest": forecast_latest,
                       "Chosen_origin_i": latest_origin, "Chosen_horizon": chosen_h}, index=verif_index)
    return df

def plot_forecast_vs_actual(forecast_df, forecast_start_date=None, forecast_end_date=None, marker=""):
    if forecast_start_date is None:
        forecast_start_date = forecast_df.index[0]
    if forecast_end_date is None:
        forecast_end_date = forecast_df.index[-1]

    mape = calc_mape(torch.asarray(forecast_df.loc[forecast_start_date:forecast_end_date, "Actual"]), torch.asarray(forecast_df.loc[forecast_start_date:forecast_end_date, "Median"]))
    mape = np.round(mape, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    plt.plot(forecast_df.loc[forecast_start_date:forecast_end_date, :].index, forecast_df.loc[forecast_start_date:forecast_end_date, "Actual"], label="Actual", linewidth=2)
    plt.plot(forecast_df.loc[forecast_start_date:forecast_end_date, :].index, forecast_df.loc[forecast_start_date:forecast_end_date, "Median"], label="Ensemble Median", linewidth=2, linestyle="--", marker=marker)

    plt.suptitle(f"Rolling Multi-step Ensemble Median Forecast vs Actual")
    plt.title(f"{forecast_start_date.date()} - {forecast_end_date.date()}\nMAPE = {mape}%")
    plt.xlabel("Date")
    plt.ylabel("Value")
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Conclusion:
This work proposes a novel high-capacity, ensemble N-BEATS architecture to predict the VIX index, trained over two decades of past data and tested on a truly out-of-sample one-year test set. Through the combination of nine models with different lookback horizons within a median ensemble, the method is able to effectively incorporate both short-term volatility dynamics as well as longer-term structural trends. The results have good predictive power with a Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) of $5.68 \%$ for the test horizon, with much smaller errors $(\sim 2 \%)$ for low-volatility regimes. The findings indicate that the proposed ensemble method not only generalizes well across different volatility regimes but also delivers stable and strong performance without the need for advanced feature engineering. Thanks to its scalability, interpretability, and efficiency, the model holds excellent prospects for production deployment in real-world volatility forecasting and risk management systems.
